      <h2>Blade Selection for Tree Roots</h2>
      <p>The best reciprocating saw is only as effective as the blade you put on it. For tree roots 2 to 6 inches thick, use an 8-inch or 12-inch pruning blade with 4-6 teeth per inch. The wide tooth gullet clears sawdust and mud efficiently. For roots with embedded soil or rocks, a carbide-grit blade survives contact with abrasive material that would dull a standard bi-metal blade in seconds. Avoid demolition blades with fine teeth for root cutting they load up with wet wood fibers and stop cutting. Arborists and landscape contractors commonly carry a separate pruning blade for roots and a demolition blade for pipe and nail-embedded lumber, switching between them as the job demands.</p>

      <h2>Conclusion</h2>
      <p>Cutting tree roots is one of the most demanding applications for a reciprocating saw because the material is wet, dirty, and variable in density. The DEWALT 12-amp corded model remains the benchmark for sustained heavy cutting where a power source is available. Its 1,899 five-star ratings reflect a decade of field performance in exactly this kind of work. For cordless operation, the Bosch Professional GSA 18V-LI C combines the highest stroke rate with reliable blade retention and battery runtime. And for contractors on a budget who need a capable saw for occasional root cutting and general demolition, the Ryobi P516 delivers adequate power at a fraction of the premium-platform entry cost. Match the saw to how often you will make the cut, and invest the savings in quality pruning blades, where the real cutting happens.</p>

